<section xml:id="group">
  <title>Introduction to groups</title>
  
  <definition xml:id="def-group">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>group</term> is a set <m>G</m> along with a binary algebraic operation <m>\cdot</m> 
        that satisfies the following properties:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Closure:</em> For any <m>a,b</m> in <m>G</m>, it follows that <m>a\cdot b</m> in <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Associativity:</em> For any <m>a,b, c</m> in <m>G</m>, it follows that <m>(a\cdot b)\cdot c = a\cdot (b\cdot c)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Identity:</em> There is an element (usually denoted) <m>e</m> in <m>G</m>, such that for any <m>a</m> in <m>G</m>, 
              we have that <m>e\cdot a=a</m> and <m>a\cdot e=a</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Inverses:</em> For any <m>a</m> in <m>G</m>, we there is a <m>a^{-1}</m> in <m>G</m> so that <m>a\cdot a^{-1}=e</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <problem xml:id="problem-maybegroups">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each of the following, determine if the given set and operation for a group.  
        If they do not, show for which operations precisely they fail.
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Positive integers under addition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Positive integers under multiplication.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Integers under addition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Integers under multiplication.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Positive reals under addition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Positive under multiplication.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Reals under addition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Reals under multiplication.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Polynomials under addition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Polynomials under composition.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Rock, Paper, Scissors under winner (or tie).
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Bijections from <m>\{1, 2, 3\}\to \{1, 2, 3\}</m> under composition.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </problem>
  <problem xml:id="problem-D4">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the collection of the 8 possible symmetries of a square, 4 rotations
         (including the 0 degree identity rotation) and the 4 reflections:
          <image source="img/D4.jpg" width="%">
            <description>Symmetries of a Square</description>
          </image>

          Let composition <m>\circ</m> be the operation.
          
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>R1\circ R2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>R2\circ M1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>M1\circ R2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>D1\circ D2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the inverse of <m>M1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Fill out an 8 by 8 <q>multiplication</q> table of the possible operations.  What patterns do you notice?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine if this set and operation form a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathbb{Z}_n</m> denote the <term>integers modulo <m>n</m></term>.  For example <m>\mathbb{Z}_4</m>
        is the set <m>\{0,1,2,3\}</m> where <m>2+1=3, 3+1=0, 3+2=1</m> etc.. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Pick 4 different <m>n</m>'s at least 2.  Show that <m>\mathbb{Z}_n</m> for your choices for a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\mathbb{Z}_n</m> is always a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>D_n</m> denote the symmetries of a regular <m>n</m>-sided polygon.  
        For example in <xref ref="problem-D4"/> describes the symmetries of a regular <m>4</m>-gon ie a square.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Pick 3 different <m>n</m>'s at least 3.  Show that <m>D_n</m> for your choices for a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>D_n</m> is always a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>S_n</m> denote the bijections from an <m>n</m> element set to itself.  
        For example in <xref ref="problem-maybegroups"/> describes <m>S_3</m> at the end.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Pick 3 different <m>n</m>'s at least 2.  Show that <m>S_n</m> for your choices for a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>S_n</m> is always a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that identities have to be unique.  (What happens if there was a second identity <m>e'</m>?)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that right inverses are left inverses.  (If there were <m>b, c</m> so that <m>ab=e</m> and <m>ca=e</m>, what would happen?)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </problem>

  <definition xml:id="def-abelian">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A group is said to be <em>abelian</em> if for any <m>a,b\in G, a\cdot b = b\cdot a</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  
  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In the groups you identified in <xref ref="problem-maybegroups"/>, which groups are abelian?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      Given a group <m>G</m> a subset <m>H\subseteq G</m> is a <em>subgroup</em> of <m>G</m> if 
      <m>H</m> is also a group with the same operation.
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <problem>
    <task>
      <p>
        Show that even integers are a subgroup of the integers.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Determine if multiples of three are a subgroup of the integers.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Determine if odd integers are a subgroup of the integers.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Find 3 different subgroups of <m>D_8</m>
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Given <m>D_n</m> are the collections of rotations a subgroup?
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Given <m>D_n</m> are the collections of reflections a subgroup?
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Label the corners of a square <m>1, 2, 3, 4</m>.  How can this help us find a subgroup of <m>S_4</m> of size 8?
      </p>
    </task>
  </problem>

  

  
